# Wireshark Phishing Investigation

## Overview

This project documents a simulated Business Email Compromise (BEC) investigation completed as part of the CodePath Intermediate Cybersecurity course. Using Wireshark, I analyzed packet capture (PCAP) files containing SMTP traffic to investigate suspicious email activity.

The objective was to identify phishing emails, examine email header information, and use network traffic analysis to determine the source of the simulated attack. This project strengthened my understanding of how packet analysis and SMTP metadata support phishing investigations and incident response.

---

## Objectives

* Analyze network traffic captured in PCAP files using Wireshark.
* Filter SMTP traffic to isolate email communications.
* Differentiate legitimate emails from phishing emails.
* Examine SMTP headers and packet metadata during an investigation.
* Practice documenting findings from a cybersecurity investigation.

---

## Scenario

A company suspected a Business Email Compromise (BEC) attack after employees received suspicious emails requesting financial transactions. My role was to analyze the provided network traffic, identify the phishing activity, and investigate the origin of the attack using Wireshark.

---

## Tools Used

* Wireshark
* PCAP Files
* SMTP Protocol
* Network Packet Analysis

---

## Investigation Process

1. Opened the provided PCAP files in Wireshark.
2. Applied SMTP display filters to isolate email traffic.
3. Examined packet details and email conversations.
4. Compared legitimate and suspicious email messages.
5. Reviewed SMTP metadata and email headers to understand message routing.
6. Identified indicators of phishing activity and documented the investigation process.

